“Yes, sir. They should be on their way by now, and we gave them time to pack up food from the cafeteria.” 05:00 exactly, Exodus is gathered at the vehicle segment. Lieutenant Xu stands on a box, beginning to speak.
“We will head to the I-131 front-line base 50 miles outside of Ianlos City. We will support the ongoing siege operation, and then attack Ianlos City, clearing out the rebels there. We will use this as our base, advancing into the mountainous area.” Lieutenant Xu explained. “Take your team, and get ready to depart.”
The platoon disperses, with each squad climbing onto a tank under the leadership of their respective squad leaders. Kolen climbed onto a tank at the front of the convoy, sitting with Nimich, Kress, and two new recruits. Kolen remembered that they had arrived just a few days ago, but didn't know them well. He sat at the edge of the tank, with his legs dangling in the air, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, and connecting them to his earpiece and throat microphone.
“Hey, Kolen, is Harris still got Snowball?” Nimich asked after they had settled in.
“You mean the chicken he swiped?” Kolen recalled the scene that morning when they had stolen chickens from the farm. “Yeah, I'm sure of it.”
Kolen looked at another tank and saw Harris and his squad. He glimpsed a small chicken pecking around from behind Harris's backpack.
"That's right, he even keeps that chicken," Kolen replied, and the hatch on the tank turret creaked open as the gunner appeared before them.
"All tanks have departed," the gunner said calmly and clearly into the radio. The armor platoon's tanks and the Stryker armor vehicle engines roared to life and began moving forward. Kolen's Cronus tank eased off the brakes and moved forward, falling into line. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Italian plain. Winter's storm had frozen the wetlands and forests, but the mud remained.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Kolen remembered his name was Oslen) asked, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the start of the war?"
"That's right, I've been here since the Firestorm operation," Kolen replied. "We thought it would all be over in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"It's not just an underestimation."  Nimitz also joined the conversation. "Their weapons and forces exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and last month shot down the Erebus. Damn it, we should be able to see it on the road."
"Well, I'll bravely fight for the Federation."  Ossen said firmly, "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You're saying that now, but from what I see, most of the young conscripts like you, as soon as they hear gunfire, they're trembling with fear," Cress said.
"We'll just see,"  Cullen smiled and said. Ossen did not speak again.
"Exodus deputy commander! Exodus commander!"  Cullen's radio device made a call. "We've detected a heat signal at 20 degrees right front, 350 meters away."
Kalen climbed onto the tank, put on his optical goggles. Switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw a heat signal far away.
"Yes, I see them," Kalen said into the throat microphone.
"Are they enemies?" another new recruit, Natalia, asked.
"Can't tell," Kalen said, opening the microphone. "Exodus link, don't fire unless attacked, first lure them out."
As they got closer, the weak heat signal transformed from a vague spot into a clearer outline. One of them ran to a place, picked something up, then ran back to the small hill. Then, they all lay down and entered the firing position.
“We've encountered the enemy!” Lieutenant Xiao shouted through the radio as an orange tracer round shot out from the mountain's peak.
“Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 yards. Fire!” The tank commander shouted through the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3's main cannons fired, and the shells whirred towards the mountain, exploding and sending mud and debris flying into the air.
“Send out a sentry robot!” Knox shouted, observing the mountain through binoculars. A "Hellhound's" rear hatch opened, and a soldier without a weapon stepped out, wearing a custom-made headset. He yelled orders into a square microphone, and two "Sentries" robots responded, their long, thin metal arms and legs moving forward, sprinting rapidly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were hung on their backs.
“Kill or capture?” Cres asked, observing and questioning at the same time.
“Looks like we're going to capture them alive,” Cullen speculated, seeing the two Sentries robots disappear into the ashes and smoke. The mountain echoed with cries and gunfire, but it soon subsided. After a while, the two Sentries robots returned, dragging a person, leaving a trail of footprints in the snow and mud. After arriving at the safe area, the robots tossed the prisoner to the ground, and he landed heavily, groaning in pain.
He struggled to get up, Lieutenant Xiao walked over.
"Three died, sir," the sentry robot replied.  "The rest have fled on foot."
Lieutenant Xiao nodded, turned to Colonel Corn and Kreis standing nearby and said, "Can you two take this guy away?"
